Journal of Experimental Child Psychology

Volume 188, December 2019, 104675

Pay to play: Children’s emerging ability to use acts of generosity for selfish ends

Author links open overlay panelFelixWarnekenaCarlaSebastián-EnescobNatalie E.BenjamincKerrie A.Pielochd
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jecp.2019.104675Get rights and content

Highlights

•

We studied the development of strategic giving where ostensibly generous acts serve ulterior selfish ends.

•

5- and 7-year-olds learned to share a valuable resource when it prompted a recipient to choose the child over another potential play partner.

•

This form of strategic giving to influence subsequent partner choice adds to our understanding of the various forms of reciprocity as they develop in children.

•

We discuss whether future-directed thinking could explain the developmental emergence of such strategic giving.

Abstract

Adults will offer favors to advance their standing and solicit a favor in return, using ostensibly prosocial acts strategically for selfish ends. Here we assessed the developmental emergence of such strategic behaviors in which individuals are generous to elicit future reciprocation from others. In a novel experimental paradigm with children aged 3 to 7 years, we tested whether children are willing to share more valuable resources when this act could prompt subsequent reciprocation. In an Experimental condition, children could share a more attractive or less attractive resource with a person who they knew would subsequently choose to play a game with either the children or another individual. In the Control condition, children knew the person would play alone. Across two studies, we found that over repeated trials, 5- and 7-year-olds, but not 3-year-olds, learned to share more valuable resources in the Experimental condition than in the Control condition. This shows that older age groups were able to quickly learn how to influence the subsequent partner choice in a novel situation. We address theoretical questions about the various types of reciprocity as being supported by different psychological mechanisms and discuss whether the current results could be explained by children’s emerging ability for future-directed thinking.

Introduction

Sometimes people are nice to others for purely selfish reasons; a person may offer favors with the ulterior motive to elicit a favor in return. This can take rather subtle forms, such as ingratiating oneself to advance one’s standing, and it can also occur in clear cases of bribery or corruption, where people strategically give to manipulate another’s decision. What is common across these various behaviors is that people pay a cost in the present while anticipating a return benefit in the future. This requires some understanding of how one’s own behavior can influence how others behave in return, initiating a reciprocal interaction rather than simply responding to how they have been treated in the past. That is, this behavior is inherently future directed given that people do not simply respond to a partner’s previous behavior (such as in tit for tat) but rather act strategically in the present to elicit future reciprocation. It is currently unknown at what age children begin to engage in such a sophisticated form of reciprocity.

Theoretical models of reciprocal behaviors

Studying different forms of reciprocity in children is critical to understanding the basis of human cooperation. Theoretical models have shown how reciprocity can generate cooperation among non-kin in various, often intricate ways (Axelrod and Hamilton, 1981, Nowak, 2006, Trivers, 1971). As an illustration of the various ways in which this can occur, consider how reciprocity can result from repeated interactions with you and me exchanging favors over time: by you choosing who to interact with and others choosing whether to interact with you, by you looking back at how others have treated you, by you looking back at how others have treated others, or by you looking ahead at how others might treat you. To account for this variety, theoretical models have distinguished between direct reciprocity, where individuals exchange favors directly with each other over repeated encounters, and indirect reciprocity, where individuals cooperate based on how a potential cooperative partner has interacted with third parties and consider how their own behavior may in turn affect their reputation in the eyes of others (Nowak, 2006). Another critical distinction is between partner fidelity, where individuals decide how to interact with a given partner (e.g., cooperate, defect), and partner choice, where individuals choose who to interact with (e.g., shun defectors, seek out cooperators; Bull & Rice, 1991).

Last but not least, it is important to make the distinction between past-driven retrospective reciprocity versus future-oriented prospective reciprocity. Specifically, several nonhuman animals are known to engage in forms of past-driven reciprocity, for example, chimpanzees preferentially cooperating with individuals who cooperated with them in the past (Melis et al., 2008, Schmelz et al., 2017). By contrast, forms of direct reciprocity, in which individuals act strategically in anticipation of a future payoff or manage their reputation in third-party contexts, are rare in nonhuman animals if they exist at all (Brosnan and de Waal, 2002, Engelmann et al., 2012, Hammerstein, 2003, Schino and Aureli, 2009). Therefore, reciprocity is not a single behavior but rather a family of behaviors that is likely underlaid by various psychological mechanisms.

Studies on children’s reciprocal behaviors

Developmental psychology is only beginning to chart the ontogenetic emergence of the various forms of reciprocity. Although some forms of reciprocity have been studied in some age groups, we are a long way from being able to even describe the developmental trajectories of critical reciprocal behaviors, let alone explain what psychological mechanisms account for their emergence (Engelmann and Rapp, 2018, Leimgruber, 2018, Warneken, 2018). Here we review the existing literature on reciprocity in young children, organized by the theoretically important distinctions mentioned above (see Engelmann and Rapp, 2018, Leimgruber, 2018, and Warneken, 2018, for comprehensive reviews).

The majority of published studies have focused on children’s past-driven reciprocity in response to a partner’s previous behavior. One set of studies tested children’s preferences to interact with either a cooperator or a defector in partner choice situations. When confronted with this choice, young children from around 2 or 3 years of age prefer to interact with a person who was previously cooperative over a noncooperator. This includes second-party cases where one agent was mean and the other was nice to the child (e.g., Dunfield & Kuhlmeier, 2010) and third-party cases where children witnessed how the potential partners had treated others before (e.g., Vaish, Carpenter, & Tomasello, 2010). Both are examples of reciprocity in terms of partner choice, where children respond to the prior cooperativeness (vs. meanness) of other individuals.

Another group of studies looked at contingent reciprocity in partner fidelity situations, measuring whether children’s level of sharing was influenced by a partner’s prior behavior. These studies show that by 3.5 years of age, children share more resources when interacting with a cooperator than when interacting with a defector (Warneken & Tomasello, 2013) and cooperate contingent on a peer’s prior behavior by 5 years of age (House, Henrich, Sarnecka, & Silk, 2013). In addition, 5-year-olds share more when interacting with a partner who reciprocates in a tit-for-tat manner than when no reciprocation is possible (Sebastian-Enesco & Warneken, 2015) and develop a strategy of turn taking when one of two children can obtain a valuable resource every other time (Melis, Grocke, Kalbitz, & Tomasello, 2016). By 6 to 8 years of age, children reciprocate by favoring individuals who share with them, even overriding concerns of fairness when they are placed in a competitive context to accrue as many resources as possible (Shaw, DeScioli, & Olson, 2012).

Lastly, several experiments have studied indirect reciprocity by testing whether children consider how their own reputation might be at stake when deciding whether to cooperate with others. Beginning at around 5 years of age, children share more (e.g., Engelmann et al., 2013, Leimgruber et al., 2012) and cheat less (Engelmann et al., 2012, Fu et al., 2016) when they are being observed by others. In a comprehensive review, Engelmann and Rapp (2018) concluded that by 5 years of age, children engage in implicit reputation management, whereby they behave differently based on whether they are being observed and who is observing them. By 8 years of age, children begin to engage in explicit reputation management, whereby they can reason about self-presentational motives and strategies that they and others can employ. Specifically, studies using hypothetical scenarios have shown that 8-year-olds, but not younger children, understand why someone would choose to make statements that reflect more positively on the self (Aloise-Young, 1993, Banerjee and Yuill, 1999, Hill and Pillow, 2006). Moreover, 8-year-olds, but not younger children, understood that story characters wanted to make sure their sharing occurred in public rather than in private because they had an ulterior of making a good impression (Heyman, Barner, Heumann, & Schenck, 2014).

Taken together, these studies show that during early to middle childhood, children engage in various forms of contingent reciprocity. Current evidence suggests that strategically manipulating how others think of oneself requires skills that are not yet available to young children. However, it is also possible that children engage in impression management but find it difficult to reflect on and report the reasons for their behavior.

Retrospective versus prospective reciprocity

One limitation of this prior work is that studies on direct reciprocity have focused on past-driven, or retrospective, reciprocity. Specifically, positive results of children’s contingent reciprocation can be explained by children responding to how the partner has treated them in the past without necessarily anticipating how the partner will treat them in the future. For example, in Sebastian-Enesco and Warneken (2015), children could learn over repeated trials that the partner copied their behavior in a tit-for-tat manner. House et al., 2013, Melis et al., 2016 showed that, in fact, the peer’s own current sharing was predicted by the peer’s prior sharing. These studies are intriguing because they suggest an emergence of contingent reciprocity between 3 and 5 years of age. However, these designs cannot determine whether children’s behaviors were actually future oriented. Under a rich interpretation, children share more in the present because they anticipate that the partner will reciprocate in kind in the future. Under a more parsimonious interpretation, children simply copy how the partner has shared with them in the past in a tit-for-tat manner.

What is known about children’s ability to engage in future-directed, or prospective, reciprocity? We know of only three studies that measured whether children’s prosocial behavior is influenced by potential future reciprocation of some form: Kenward et al., 2015, Engelmann et al., 2013, and Herrmann, Engelmann, and Tomasello (2019); however, these studies did not examine the questions raised in our study. Kenward et al. (2015) presented 4- to 8-year-olds with two individuals; both stated their intention to reciprocate, but only one had actual resources to do it. An adult model then shared with the “rich” reciprocator over the “poor” reciprocator. When children were instructed to give a resource away, they tended to do what the adult model had done. It is possible that children assessed who would be able to reciprocate. Alternatively, perhaps children copied the adult model without insight into why exactly the adult had engaged in this behavior (imitation and overimitation are common in this age group). Moreover, although this study assessed who should receive their resource, children did not themselves decide whether or not they wanted to share given that they were forced to give away the only resource they had. From this study, thus, it is not known whether children are willing to pay a cost to elicit future reciprocation.

Beyond studies of direct reciprocity, Engelmann et al., 2013, Herrmann et al., 2019 assessed whether children consider the possibility of indirect reciprocity. In Engelmann et al. (2013), 5-year-olds increased their sharing toward an absent peer when a third-party peer observer could later share with the child participants. More relevant for our theoretical purposes, Herrmann et al. (2019) found that 8-year-olds, but not 5-year-olds, were more likely to share when this behavior could increase the chance of being chosen as a game partner by a third-party observer. Altogether these findings suggest that by at least 5 years of age children consider how their own sharing may affect their reputation with regard to third parties (Engelmann et al., 2013) and that around 8 years of age they also consider how to manipulate the observer’s behavior (Herrmann et al., 2019). However, these two studies differ in a significant way from the phenomenon we were testing in the current studies. In these two studies, the person who children would interact with in the future was a passive onlooker; hence, children could not curry a favor to the onlooker to influence her behavior (indirect rather than direct reciprocity). Thus, although both Herrmann et al., 2019, Engelmann et al., 2013 can be interpreted as evidence of future-directed sharing, neither addressed whether children would pay a cost to an individual to directly influence the individual’s subsequent behavior. In other words, children made decisions while potentially trying to influence a third party but did not address whether children would try to gain a favor by directly benefitting the person who could later reciprocate. In addition, only children aged 5 years or older were tested, raising the question of when such future-directed reciprocity emerges in development.

In summary, existing research shows that contingent reciprocity emerges between 3 and 5 years of age, with children engaging in costly cooperation more often when the interaction is iterated. However, it is unclear whether children do this in anticipation of future reciprocation or are simply copying the other’s prior behavior. When they are in the role of a decider, young children choose a partner who was cooperative toward them in the past (Leimgruber, 2018). However, no study has tested what young children do in the reverse situation, where they could cooperate in order to influence whether someone chooses them over another individual in a partner choice situation. Moreover, research shows that between 5 and 8 years of age children begin to be affected by observation through third parties, but it is not known whether children will strategically offer resources to those who judge them in order to directly solicit favorable treatment over other individuals. Lastly, given that most existing studies tested only one or two age groups, wider age ranges are needed to capture the emergence and further development of reciprocity. We are not aware of any study that has examined the emergence of the fairly sophisticated form of reciprocity targeted here—strategically paying a cost in the present to be chosen as a social partner in the future.

The current studies

We tested the developmental emergence of strategic giving behavior in terms of costly sharing with a beneficiary to influence a subsequent partner choice. Children could be generous (by sharing an attractive resource) or not (by sharing a less attractive resource) with a game owner who would later choose a play partner. Another person, the competitor, could also choose to share the more or less attractive resource with the game owner. The game owner expressed a preference for the more attractive resource and chose the play partner based on who had been more generous toward her. Our dependent measure was whether the child would share the more or less attractive resource. Note that the paradigm was not designed to test children’s prosociality per se (whether or not they share); rather, it was designed to test children’s willingness to share a relatively more attractive resource.

Based on work on children’s explicit understanding of impression management, we predicted that 7-year-olds would be willing and able to sacrifice a valuable resource in the present in order to be chosen as a play partner later. Our age group of 5-year-olds was of particular interest because research is inconclusive as to whether this age group would be able to succeed in a task where the children could directly influence another person’s subsequent partner choice. On the one hand, children are able to engage in certain forms of direct and indirect reciprocity that, as discussed in detail above, may or may not require the anticipation of another person’s future behavior. The success of 5-year-olds in our task would be congruent with the rich interpretation of prior studies, with 5-year-olds being more cooperative because they consider future effects of their behavior. On the other hand, studies of explicit impression management and an interactive task by Herrmann et al. (2019) suggest that when children need to assess how a third party’s observation in the present may influence how this observer would act toward them in the future, children often fail. Therefore, from this line of work, one would infer that 5-year-olds are not yet capable of sharing specifically to influence subsequent partner choice. We predicted that 3-year-olds would not engage in this strategic behavior and instead would keep the attractive resource for themselves based on previous findings that they fail to reciprocate in iterated interactions and are not yet influenced by reputational concerns. We report two studies; Study 1 establishes the phenomenon with 5- and 7-year-olds, and Study 2 replicates and extends these findings with a modified procedure across 3-, 5-, and 7-year-olds.

Study 1

Method

Participants

The final sample consisted of 64 children, with equal numbers of 5-year-olds (M = 5.4 years, range = 5.0–5.9) and 7-year-olds (M = 7.5 years, range = 7.1–7.9) and equal numbers of boys and girls per age group. An additional 9 children were excluded because they did not express a preference for the attractive resource at the beginning of the session (7 5-year-olds and 2 7-year-olds), and 1 child was excluded because of video-recording problems. Participants were recruited from a child database from a large city in the United States. Parents reported mixed socioeconomic backgrounds, and 68% described their children as White/Caucasian, 6% as Black, 5% as Asian, and the remaining as other or unspecified race.

Overview of design and procedure

Children were randomly assigned to either an Experimental or Control condition (between participants). In the Experimental condition, the games were played by two players, and the game owner selected either the child or the competitor as her play partner. In the Control condition, games were modified so that only one player could play; therefore, the game owner always played alone. There were four trials, each with a new game. In each trial, children received an attractive fish sticker and an unattractive circle sticker to divide between themselves and the game owner (Fig. A1). Children made their sharing decision in private before the game owner returned. The game owner compared what she received from the child and the competitor and then chose a partner to play with (Experimental condition) or played alone (Control condition). Throughout testing, children were asked a series of comprehension checks to ensure that they understood that (a) the other players (including the game owner) preferred the more attractive resource, and (b) the game was either a two-player game (Experimental condition) or a one-player game (Control condition). All included children answered the comprehension checks correctly.

Setup and materials

We developed four different games that could be played either together (two-player game for the Experimental condition) or alone by the game owner (one-player game for the Control condition). For example, in the maze game, one player moved a mouse through the first half of a maze and the partner took over for the second half. In the one-person version, the game owner moved the mouse through the whole maze on her own. See Fig. 1 and Appendix A for details of the maze game and the other three games.

Procedure

Children were tested individually in a testing room while parents watched the study on video from a separate observation room. Here we first describe the main procedure of the Experimental condition and then specify which aspects were different in the Control condition.

During a short warm-up, children were introduced to the experimenter and the two other players (all female). Everyone was addressed by their names (rather than by their roles). For ease of comprehension, they are referred to here by their roles, that is, the game owner and the competitor. The game owner was seated at a child-sized table across from the child and the other player, who sat next to each other. Each game used in a given trial was placed on the table between the game owner and the players. The experimenter knelt next to the table while giving instructions.

Game introduction

The game owner sat in front of the game while the experimenter explained that this was a two-player game where the game owner could decide whether she wanted to play it with the child or the competitor. Only two people would be able to play the game. However, the experimenter explained that they would first play the “giving game.”

Sharing task (“giving game”)

Each player had a colorful fish sticker (attractive resource) and a plain circle sticker (unattractive resource) (see Appendix A). During a sticker preference test, the child and the other two players were asked which sticker they liked better (players said that they liked the fish sticker better), followed by a comprehension check to ensure that the child understood that the players also liked the fish sticker better. The experimenter explained that during the giving game the child and the competitor could decide which sticker they want to keep by placing it on their own bag and which one to give away by placing it on the game owner’s bag. The child always went first. The competitor and the experimenter went behind a screen in the back of the room while the game owner and the child stayed in their seats. The game owner said, “I wonder which sticker you’re going to give me, and then I can choose who to play my game with.” The child made his or her choice. Then the child went behind the screen while it was the competitor’s turn. The competitor always made the opposite choice of the child.

Partner choice

Everybody returned and sat down at the table. After a game comprehension check where children were asked whether this was a one-player or two-player game, the experimenter told the game owner that she could now choose who to play with. The game owner picked up each sticker, stated who gave it to her, and then announced who she would play with, always choosing the person who had given her the fish sticker. The game owner and the chosen player then played the game for about 15 s.

The Control condition followed the same procedure except that a one-player game was used and, thus, no partner choice occurred. Correspondingly, the game owner said, “I wonder which sticker you’re going to give me and then I can play my game by myself.” At the end of each trial, the game owner took the stickers and played the game by herself in front of the child and competitor.

For each trial, the experimenter brought in a new game and went through the same procedure, including comprehension checks. After two trials, we included a short motivational play period where the child could play a game by himself or herself that was not used in the main test (e.g., a zigzag ramp into which they could insert balls that disappeared).

At the end of the session, the experimenter asked the child posttest questions. She asked why the child sometimes gave the fish sticker (or, alternatively, why the child had always kept it): “When we were playing the giving game, how did you decide which sticker to give to [game owner]?” In the Experimental condition, she also asked the child why he or she thought the game owner had chosen to play with the partners she had selected: “Why did the game owner sometimes choose you and sometimes choose [competitor]?”

Coding and preliminary results

Our main dependent measure was whether children gave the more attractive or less attractive sticker to the game owner. All coding was done live and was double-checked from video. To assess interrater reliability, we randomly selected 7 children per age group (45%) who were coded from video by an independent rater who was blind to condition. There were no disagreements. The included children passed all comprehension checks, correctly remembering which sticker the game owner preferred (100% of trials) and correctly identifying whether the game was a one- or two-player game (97% of trials).

Children’s responses to posttest questions (explanations) were transcribed verbatim from video, and the text was then coded by a research assistant who was blind to condition, age, and the child’s choices and was unaware of the hypotheses. A reliability coder independently rated all utterances as well.

We used the following mutually exclusive categories for children’s explanations of their own giving behavior: (1) personal preference, where answers are only about the child’s own desire (e.g., “Because I liked the fish sticker,” “I like orange”); (2) game owner preference, where answers include a reference to the game owner’s preference or prosocial motives (e.g., “Because she liked the fish sticker better,” “Because that’s fair”); (3) strategic motives, where the game or the player selection is mentioned (e.g., “I wanted to play the game,” “She picked the one who gave her the fish sticker”); and (4) other, which included answers that were unrelated to the child’s own or the other’s preferences (e.g., “I wanted it to be a pattern,” circular descriptions, “don’t know”). Cohen’s kappa was excellent (κ = .96).

For children’s explanations of the game owner’s choice behavior, we coded as follows: (1) giving event, where the child mentioned only his or her own and/or the competitor’s giving behavior but not the connection to the partner choice (e.g., “Because I gave her what she wanted,” “Because she gave her the fish sticker”); (2) partner choice event, where the child stated the connection between his or her own and/or the competitor’s giving behavior and the game owner’s partner choice (e.g., “I gave it and she picked me,” “Who gave her what she wanted to play the game”); and (3) other (e.g., no answer, circular description, “don’t know”). We regarded both categories (1) and (2) as answers that reflected children’s understanding of strategic giving behavior, with category (2) being a more elaborate description of this concept. Cohen’s kappa was excellent (κ = .90).

All disagreements were resolved by discussions between coders to create a final data set. There were no missing trials. Preliminary analyses showed no effect of gender on children’s choices or explanations; therefore, this variable was not included in further analyses.

We analyzed the data as generalized linear mixed models (GLMMs) with the “lme4” package in R (Version 3.6.0; Bates, Machler, Bolker, & Walker, 2015), with children’s choices as binary response terms using a binomial distribution (attractive sticker = 1, unattractive sticker = 0). Model comparisons were done using likelihood ratio tests (LRTs). We first compared a null model, which included participant ID, against a full model, which included the predictor variables of interest defined below, hence testing whether the inclusion of predictors provided a better fit to the data than participant ID alone. We also considered the inclusion of trial number as a random effect nested within participant, but for both studies this resulted in nonconvergence and singular fits. Following Matuschek, Kliegl, Vasishth, Baayen, and Bates (2017), we implemented a hypothesis-driven model selection approach to avoid overfitting. We assessed the effect of individual predictor variables by dropping terms from the full model and testing whether their removal decreased fit significantly using LRTs. Figures were created with the “ggplot2” package and the “effects” package to estimate confidence intervals. Both data and code can be accessed via the Open Science Framework at https://osf.io/7d93j/?view_only=34fb86a5fdc84dc2b184892ee99d2239.

Results

Our main question was whether children would be overall more likely to share the attractive sticker in the Experimental condition than in the Control condition. In addition, we examined whether children changed their behavior over trials. We used a hypothesis-driven analysis approach and ran model comparisons with sharing of the attractive sticker as a binary response term, age group (5 or 7 years), condition (Experimental or Control), and trial (1, 2, 3, or 4) as fixed effects, and participant ID as a random effect to account for repeated testing. Fig. 2 displays the estimated rates of sharing the attractive sticker as a function of condition and trial for 5- and 7-year-olds, respectively.

This full model provided a significantly better fit than a null model that contained only participant ID, LRT χ2 = 48.30, df = 7, p < .001. Age did not interact with condition or trial and, hence, was included as a main effect in further model comparisons. We found a significant interaction of condition and trial, LRT χ2 = 4.18, df = 1, p < .05, and a main effect of age, LRT χ2 = 6.80, df = 1, p < .01 (see Table S1 in the online supplementary material for the model output).

We next looked at children’s first-trial behavior. Children did not yet reliably differentiate between conditions in the first trial, but they did so from the second trial onward. This is apparent from the confidence intervals in Fig. 2 and was confirmed using Fisher’s exact tests (Trial 1: ns; Trial 2: ps < .05, n = 32 for both age groups). Taken together, the interaction of trial and condition, as well as analyses of individual trials, showed that children did not immediately share more in the Experimental condition than in the Control condition, but they quickly learned how to influence the subsequent partner choice.

To gain a better understanding of children’s reasoning, we examined children’s explanations. When asked about the reason for their own giving behavior (sharing either the attractive or unattractive resource), 5- and 7-year-olds showed the same pattern, revealing a significant difference between conditions by being more likely to refer either to the game owner preference (e.g., “Because she liked the fish sticker better”) or to strategic motives (e.g., “She picked the one who gave her the fish sticker”) in the Experimental condition and providing more explanations mentioning only their own preference for the sticker (e.g., “Because I liked the fish sticker”) in the Control condition (Table 1).

Regarding children’s explanation of the game owner’s partner choice (i.e., why the game owner chose either the child or the other player) in the Experimental condition, all 7-year-olds and a majority of 5-year-olds referenced either the giving event (e.g., “Because I gave her what she wanted”) or the connection of the giving event to the partner choice (e.g., “Who gave her what she wanted to play the game”) (see Table 2). This shows that the older children could clearly articulate the reason for the game owner’s choice and could relate it to their own prior sharing behavior. Taken together, the analyses of children’s explanations support the main results about children’s sharing behavior by revealing that children gave different explanations for their own choices in the two conditions. Moreover, older children were more likely to articulate explicitly that the game owner based her decision on the giving event.

Discussion

Results show that both 5- and 7-year-olds were more likely to share the attractive resource in the Experimental condition than in the Control condition, a pattern that quickly emerged over trials. This suggests that children strategically shared the attractive resource with the game owner so that they would be chosen to play the game with her later. However, an alternative explanation is that children did not treat this as a cooperative act of giving away something more attractive that the recipient liked but instead viewed the particular fish sticker as a “ticket” that they needed to give to play the game. To address this possibility, in Study 2 children received a unique pair of more and less attractive resources in each trial, such that there was no commonality across trials in what children would share and, thus, no simple association between an object and the game. We also examined whether children failed to reliably give away the attractive resource in the first trial because the verbal explanation about the game owner later choosing a play partner was not concrete enough for children to understand. Therefore, at the very beginning of Study 2, we included a video showing how on a prior occasion the game owner chose a play partner who could play with her while the other person needed to watch. We added 3-year-olds to further track the age of emergence of strategically giving to influence subsequent partner choice.

Study 2

Method

Participants

The final sample consisted of 96 children, with equal numbers of 3-year-olds (M = 3.6 years, range = 3.3–4.0), 5-year-olds (M = 5.4 years, range = 5.0–5.9), and 7-year-olds (M = 7.5 years, range = 7.0–7.9) and an equal number of boys and girls per age group. An additional 7 children were excluded because they expressed a preference for the nominally less attractive resource in more than half of the trials (2 3-year-olds, 2 5-year-olds, and 3 7-year-olds). Another 6 children, all 3-year-olds, were excluded because they failed comprehension checks more than half the time, namely which resource the game owner preferred (n = 4) or whether it was a one- or two-player game (n = 2), and 6 more children were excluded because of experimenter error (n = 1) or fussiness (n = 5). Children were recruited from the same database as children from Study 1. The majority of parents reported having middle-class households and held a college degree. Parents described 64% of the children as White/Caucasian, 8% as Asian, 4% as Black, and the remaining children as other or unspecified race.

Design and materials

The design was the same as that from Study 1, with children being randomly assigned to the Experimental or Control condition. There were four test trials, each with a unique game (catapult, maze, ski jump, or sailboat from Study 1), presented in counterbalanced order (Latin square). A new pair of resources (balls, erasers, rubber bands, or stickers), each with a more and less attractive version, was used for each trial. These new resource pairs all were validated in a separate preference test with 48 children (see Appendix A). The order of resources was counterbalanced (Latin square), and games and resources were systematically matched so that each type of resource appeared equally often with each game.

Procedure

We followed the same procedure as Study 1 with two modifications. First, children in the Experimental condition watched a 90-s video that showed the partner choice scenario on a previous occasion, where the actual game owner chose one of two adults to play a golf game that was not part of the actual test (see Appendix A). Hence, child participants could observe the partner choice and the consequence of being chosen or not being chosen to play the game. Importantly, the video did not include a sharing event prior to the partner choice. At the end of the video, children were also asked to say who got to play the game and who did not. In the Control condition, the video showed the game owner playing a game by herself. The second modification was that in each trial a unique set of resources was used for the sharing task, including a resource preference test now administered for each pair of resources. The procedure with Study 2 modifications is described in chronological order in what follows.

After a warm-up and the game introduction that now included the showing of the video, we administered the sharing task. The arrangement was the same, with the experimenter presenting children with a new pair of resources and asking them which one they liked better (resource preference test). The two other players always expressed a preference for the nominally more attractive resource irrespective of the child’s answer. This was followed by a preference comprehension check to assess whether the children was able to state the other player’s preferences. As in Study 1, the child and the partners then made their choices in private about which resource to give and which one to keep, followed by the partner choice and the game phase. After the end of the trial, the experimenter brought out a new game and a new pair of resources. After two trials, we included a short break where the child could play by himself or herself with the zigzag ramp. After the four test trials, the game owner invited the child to play one of the games with her. At the end of the session, the experimenter asked “When we were playing the giving game, how did you decide which toy to give to [game owner]?” and “Why did [game owner] sometimes choose you and sometimes choose [competitor]?” as in Study 1.

The Control condition was conducted in the same way as in Study 1, with the modification that children first saw a 60-s video similar to the one in the Experimental condition, only that it showed the game owner playing a game by herself and that each test trial included a novel pair of more and less attractive resources.

Coding and preliminary results

There were no missing trials. Coding of children’s choices was done in the same way as in Study 1. Once again, interrater agreement was perfect. Interrater agreement for children’s explanations was excellent, with κ = .88 for their own giving behavior and κ = .87 for the game owner’s choice.

One new feature of this procedure was that in each trial children were first asked which one of the two resources they liked better. Only children who preferred the nominally more attractive resource in at least two of the four trials were included. In our final sample, children overwhelmingly reported liking the more attractive resource (M = 88%, SE = .02) significantly above chance, t(95) = 22.59, p < .0001. Importantly, cases in which children stated a preference for the nominally less attractive resource were equally distributed between the Experimental and Control conditions (22 and 23 trials, respectively). To control for children’s resource preference, we included this variable in our analyses as a covariate (shares preference coded as 1 = yes, 0 = no). Children answered comprehension checks correctly both about the game owner’s resource preference (88% of trials) and about whether they were playing a one-player or two-player game (98% of trials). Preliminary analyses showed no effect of gender on any measures; therefore, this variable was dropped from further analyses.

Results

We used the same analysis approach as in Study 1 except that we controlled for resource preference by including it as a covariate. Therefore, our full model included participant ID as random effect, age, condition, and trial and their interactions as fixed effects, and toy preference as a covariate. Our full model significantly differed from a null model that contained only participant ID and toy preference, LRT χ2 = 68.85, df = 11, p < .001. There was a marginal three-way interaction of condition, age, and trial, LRT χ2 = 5.13, df = 2, p = .077. Thus, we considered a more parsimonious model that dropped the three-way interaction, resulting in a model that showed a significant interaction of condition with age, LRT χ2 = 33.03, df = 4, p < .001, and a significant interaction of condition with trial, LRT χ2 = 17.38, df = 2, p < .001 (see Table S2 in supplementary material for the model output). This analysis replicates the finding that children became more likely to share in the Experimental condition than in the Control condition as the study progressed and shows an effect of age. Visual inspection of the data and the marginal three-way interaction suggests that 3-year-olds differed from the other two age groups. Therefore, we also display the model with a three-way interaction (see Table S2) and conducted analyses separately by age, using the same analysis approach as before. Among 3-year-olds, none of the predictors was found to be significant. Therefore, the decisions of the 3-year-olds were unrelated to the condition and trial in which they played (p > . 90). Interestingly, the only variable that explained part of the 3-year-old data was our covariate toy preference, LRT χ2 = 84.40, df = 1, p < .001, revealing that children systematically shared the less-preferred toys regardless of the condition and trial number (see Table S3 in supplementary material for model outputs). By contrast, analyses with 5- and 7-year-olds both showed a significant interaction of condition and trial: 5-year-olds, LRT χ2 = 12.50, df = 1, p < .001; 7-year-olds, LRT χ2 = 6.10, df = 1, p = . 013 (see Table S3). In summary, Study 2 replicated the finding that over trials 5- and 7-year-olds learned to share more in the Experimental condition than in the Control condition and further revealed that 3-year-olds did not differ in their sharing across conditions.

We also replicated the finding that children quickly learned how to influence the subsequent partner choice, but did not yet do so in the first trial. Specifically, 7-year-olds showed a significant condition difference from Trial 2 onward, and 5-year-olds did so from Trial 3 onward. This can be seen from the confidence intervals in Fig. 3 and was confirmed using Fisher’s exact tests (Trial 1: ns; Trial 2: p = .004 for 7-year-olds; Trial 3: p = .03 for 5-year-olds; n = 32 for all age groups). Therefore, despite seeing a video about the partner choice, children still did not share strategically from the very first trial. Rather, 5- and 7-year-olds quickly learned to manipulate the partner choice. This suggests that children must directly experience the unfolding of events and consequences of the sharing act in order to learn how to act, which they then do consistently.

The 3-year-olds did not differentiate between conditions in any trial, systematically choosing to give away the less attractive resource (Fig. 3). This was true even though 3-year-olds answered comprehension checks correctly. That is, they knew what the game owner liked and that she would later choose who to play with, but they did not come up with the strategy to share with her to influence the outcome. Therefore, young children’s choices of what to share cannot simply be explained by a failure to understand the procedure.

Older children showed this pattern of results when new resources were used in each trial. Therefore, we could rule out the alternative explanation of Study 1 that children merely associated the game owner’s choice behavior with a specific resource such as the fish sticker. Rather, Study 2 suggests that the older children had actual insight into the contingency of doing the game owner a favor by sacrificing more attractive resources to influence the subsequent partner choice.

Analyses of children’s explanations support this interpretation. For 5- and 7-year-olds, we found a significant difference between conditions in the explanations they provided for their choices. They were more likely to provide explanations related to the game owner preferences and to strategic motives in the Experimental condition than in the Control condition. Unsurprisingly, 3-year-olds could not articulate their reasoning well, and no distinctions emerged in their explanations between conditions, reflective of their choice behavior during the game. Thus, the results for older children mirrored those of Study 1, with the majority of children in both older age groups referencing the giving event or its connection to the partner choice and ruled out the alternative hypothesis that children succeeded in Study 1 only because they had associated the fish sticker with being able to play the game.

Discussion

This experiment replicated our first study in that 5- and 7-year-olds reliably gave away more attractive resources in the Experimental condition than in the Control condition. Interestingly, children still did not strategically give in the first trial even after watching a video about the partner choice. One important new insight was that children showed this pattern of strategic giving even when new resources were used each time, ruling out more parsimonious explanations about children succeeding in Study 1 only because they viewed the fish sticker as a ticket to play the game or had simply learned an association between the fish sticker and the partner choice. The 3-year-olds did not strategically give at all but instead tended to keep the more attractive resources for themselves.

General discussion

Our experiments show that 5- and 7-year-olds, but not 3-year-olds, strategically share attractive resources to influence a subsequent partner choice. Younger children focus on the immediate benefit (associated with keeping the attractive resource), indicating that their sharing is not driven by strategic motives, whereas older children can override immediate benefits and use cooperation to influence others with an ulterior benefit in mind (having access to the game). Children’s explanations for their sharing and the game owner’s choices give further support to the idea that from 5 years of age children understand how they can manipulate others through sharing.

Our results raise the question of why this form of reciprocity emerges at around 5 years of age. Children’s future-directed thinking undergoes major changes between 3 and 5 years, including episodic foresight and planning (Atance, 2008). Therefore, one intriguing possibility is that the developmental emergence of a general cognitive ability to think and act with the future in mind applies in the social context of exchanging favors with others. In contrast to other studies on reciprocity, children would not be able to succeed in this paradigm if they just looked at how an interaction partner had treated them before. First, different commodities were used within a trial (giving away an object to influence partner choice) and between trials (in Study 2 resources were different each time), so simple copying such as in a tit-for-tat scenario was not possible. Second, the fact that in Study 2 new resources were used in each trial also rules out the possibility that children succeeded simply by copying the competitor. Third, children did not appear to copy the competitor overall, as is clear from the Control condition; if children had an inclination to just copy the competitor, who always did the opposite of what children had done in a given trial, children should have shared the attractive sticker every second trial, a pattern quite different from what was actually found. Fourth, across trials, children needed to make the first prosocial move by sacrificing the more attractive resource. Most children gave the less attractive resource in the first trial and, hence, were not chosen to play the game. A child who responded in kind in the subsequent trial would spiral into a sequence of defection (i.e., I give you the unattractive resource because you did not choose me for the game). Rather, to prompt a cooperative response by the game owner, children would need to make the first cooperative move and hand over the more attractive resource. Such a backward-looking form of reciprocity could explain the pattern of 3-year-olds and is plausible given findings that this younger age group treats people differently depending on how they have been treated in the past (e.g., Dunfield and Kuhlmeier, 2010, Warneken and Tomasello, 2013). However, it cannot explain the positive patterns of results in older children who were able to act with some insight into the game owner’s subsequent choice. Fifth, the interpretation of the behavioral results as based on some forward-looking cognition is further supported by the analysis of children’s explanations, where older children explained the game owner’s and their own decisions with reference to the sharing event and sometimes even articulated explicit strategic motives. In summary, it is likely that the developmental emergence of this sophisticated form of strategic sharing is the outcome of children’s emerging ability to think and act with the future in mind.

Older children in these studies quickly learned to adopt the strategy to sacrifice resources in order to solicit reciprocation. After witnessing the whole sequence of events from the sharing event to the partner choice in the first trial, they then consistently shared the more attractive resources with the game owner. Thus, it seems that children need minimal experience to learn the benefits of being strategically generous. However, it is possible that this experience must be firsthand in order for children to adopt this strategy. Even watching a video of the partner choice was not sufficient for children to show this kind of strategic sharing behavior from the first trial. It is also possible that children play it safe by keeping more attractive resources to themselves until they have positive evidence that the partner is actually responsive to their strategic giving. In either case, even if children’s adoption of this strategy is based on their past experience from previous trials, in a given trial children must be able to anticipate how their generous act in the present will lead to a subsequent partner choice. Therefore, although it required some experience, 5- and 7-year-olds quickly learned how to influence a subsequent partner by sacrificing a more valuable resource in the present to be chosen for a game in the future.

The youngest children rarely chose to give away the more attractive resource. Thus, it appears that despite their understanding of the procedure, they did not choose to sacrifice a resource to influence the recipient’s partner choice. We believe that this is evidence of children’s lack of ability to engage in prospective reciprocity rather than a lack of prosocial behavior altogether; a large body of research has already demonstrated that young children act prosocially in various ways, including helping, comforting, and sharing of valuable resources (Eisenberg et al., 2006, Hepach, 2016, Tomasello and Vaish, 2013, Warneken, 2018). However, our sharing task was not designed to test whether children are prosocially inclined per se; rather it was designed to test whether they are willing to sacrifice a much more attractive resource while they were left with an unattractive one. Therefore, low rates of sharing the more attractive resource are not surprising considering that people share some of their possessions but are rarely hypergenerous by sharing so much that they put themselves at a relative disadvantage, including adults who rarely give more than half away in a dictator game (Engel, 2011). Thus, although our Control condition serves as a baseline for comparisons with the Experimental condition, low rates of giving should be interpreted not as reflecting low prosociality or generosity but rather as reflecting a lack of hypergenerosity.

In summary, these studies provide new insights into the developmental trajectory of different forms of reciprocity. Prior studies show that 3-year-olds can engage in retrospective reciprocity and that 5-year-olds are capable of prospective reciprocity where they influence a partner’s future behavior eliciting direct reciprocity. There is currently debate over what kind of reputation management strategies children begin to perform by 5 to 8 years of age. Our data suggest that when children can directly curry a favor to an individual for a subsequent partner choice, 5-year-olds quickly catch on. By contrast, congruent with the theoretical model by Engelmann and Rapp (2018) and a recent finding by Herrmann et al. (2019), forms of indirect reciprocity are potentially more complex and not mastered before 8 years of age.

Limitations and future directions

Although in the current studies we established that from 5 years of age onward children sacrifice resources to win others’ favors, it is unknown when children develop a sense of bribery and corruption as potential violations of collective norms. Full-fledged bribery by adults in institutional settings has negative effects on social welfare and so is punishable, with individuals assessing the risk of discovery (Abbink et al., 2002, Dungan et al., 2014, Muthukrishna et al., 2017). Further research could explore when children begin to weigh the advantages (maximizing own profits) and disadvantages (risky behavior at the expense of others’ benefits) of corrupt relationships.

A question for future research is whether children who do not display this type of strategic sharing lack the concept or do not perform the behavior for other reasons. This is a fruitful area for future research because this complex behavior likely draws on a whole range of abilities, including future-directed thinking, behavioral control, social norms, and social preferences. As discussed above, there are strong theoretical reasons to believe that children’s future-directed thinking plays a major role given that our tasks required some level of anticipation of a partner’s subsequent behavior and the developmental pattern found here maps onto the developmental pattern of future-oriented cognition. Another contributing factor could be behavioral control such as delay of gratification given that this task required children to override an immediate benefit to obtain a delayed benefit. The role of delay of gratification for reciprocity finds support in theoretical models (Trivers, 1971) and empirical studies with children (Sebastian-Enesco & Warneken, 2015), suggesting that it could contribute to the type of prospective reciprocity tested here as well.

Conclusion

These findings provide new insights into the psychological abilities that characterize human cooperative behavior. Theoretical models of cooperation highlight the importance of making cooperative behavior selective by, for example, choosing cooperative partners reciprocally and advertising oneself as cooperative to others in a social marketplace (Baumard et al., 2013, Noë and Hammerstein, 1995). There is much debate over when in ontogeny humans develop these capacities to engage in different forms of direct and indirect reciprocity. Our results support a recent theoretical model that dissociates abilities to generate and distribute benefits, proposing that although children are able to cooperate early on, they only gradually become selective and strategic in their cooperative decision making (Warneken, 2018). Specifically, whereas forms of direct reciprocity emerge as early as late toddlerhood where children respond to a partner’s past actions or their identity (Kuhlmeier et al., 2014, Warneken, 2018), more future-oriented and directly manipulative forms of reciprocity appear to emerge later at around 5 years of age. Our findings raise the question of whether the basic form of influencing a subsequent partner choice is a potential precursor to forms of social interaction such as flattery, auctioning, and bribery as a human-unique form of reciprocity. Many animals engage in specific forms of reciprocation by preferentially cooperating with those who cooperated with them in the past. These forms of reciprocity have been explained by fairly basic and affective-based proximate mechanisms such as long-term affiliations and emotional bookkeeping (Brosnan and de Waal, 2002, Schino and Aureli, 2009). By contrast, forms of calculated reciprocity and reputation management that require more cognitive sophistication and planning have rarely been observed in nonhuman animals, if at all (Hammerstein, 2003, Schino and Aureli, 2010, Schino and Aureli, 2017). Therefore, one aspect of cooperation that may set us apart from other animals is that we learn how to bribe others.

Appendix A.

Help

Study 1

We developed four different games that could be played by either two players or one player according to condition (Experimental or Control, respectively).

The catapult game consisted of a spoon-shaped catapult (~34 cm long × 30 cm wide × 19 cm high), a butterfly net (~30 cm long), and five ping-pong balls. In the two-player version, the game owner used the catapult to launch the balls one by one so that the other player could catch them with the net. In the one-player version, the game owner shot the balls into a box placed on the floor (44 × 28 × 22 cm).

The maze game consisted of moving a mouse toy (~2.5 × 2.5 × 2.5 cm) through a maze (~60 cm long × 46 cm wide) from the starting line to the end of the maze, where a cheese toy (~2.5 × 2.5 × 2.5 cm) was placed. Players took turns using a paddle (~21 cm long × 4 cm wide) to push the mouse. The game owner was in charge for the first half of the maze (green colored), and the other player was in charge for the second half (red colored). In the one-player version, the game owner moved the mouse through the whole maze by herself.

The ski jump game consisted of a ski jump (~70 × 15 × 37 cm), a hoop (~50 cm long), and five ping-pong balls. The game owner rolled the balls one by one down the ski jump while the other player held the hoop for the balls to fly through it. In the one-player version, the game owner launched the balls one by one into a box.

In the sailboat game, players moved a toy sailboat (~8 × 6 × 8 cm) back and forth along a racing board by blowing through straws (~46 cm long × 36 cm wide). Placed across from each other, the game owner blew the sailboat from the starting line to the other player’s position, and the other player then blew it back to the initial position, and so on for 15 s. In the one-player version, the game owner blew the sailboat back and forth by herself.

Study 2

Resource preference pilot study. We first conducted a preference test to identify pairs of resources where children consistently rated one as being more attractive than the other. We tested a separate sample of 48 children aged 5 to 9 years. We showed them a pair of resources (e.g., a regular rubber band and a silly band) and asked them to indicate which one they liked better. Children made one choice for each pair of resources (order and sides counterbalanced). We identified four resources for our experiment (out of eight total resource pairs): bouncy ball versus Styrofoam ball, regular eraser versus star-shaped eraser, regular rubber band versus silly band, and plain sticker versus fish sticker (Appendix Fig. A2). Children chose the nominally more attractive resource over the less attractive resource in 98%, 89%, 89%, and 85% of trials, respectively, which is greater than expected by chance in each case (p < .0001, binomial test).

Introductory video. During the game introduction, children watched a 90-s video that showed the partner choice scenario. The experimenter explained to the child and the other two players that they would first be watching a video of something that happened yesterday. The video showed a golf game that was not part of the actual test (Appendix Fig. A3).

The actors in the video were the actual experimenter, the actual game owner, and two other adults. In the video, the experimenter first explained to the three adults the rules of the two-player game. Then the game owner chose a partner and the experimenter emphasized who gets to play the game and who does not. The game owner then played the game while the other person needed to watch. At the end of the video, the two players both said that they got to play the game in an enthusiastic manner, whereas the player who was not chosen said disappointingly that she did not get to play the game.
